According to a new paper published this week, City of Hope [ https://link.s=
bstck.com/redirect/b3d63966-98f4-4839-a79a-754098ea48f6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] researchers have develope=
d an effective and safe oral therapeutic for slowing and killing a variety =
of cancers. You can read the full press release here [ https://link.sbstck.=
com/redirect/e1558684-d063-474c-9476-2c3a050e48f5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
The core challenge with cancer drugs is somehow killing the cancerous cells=
 without killing the normal cells, too. The magic here is that the PCNA (Pr=
oliferating Cell Nuclear Antigen) that acts as scaffolding in the DNA repli=
cation process was found to be an isomer in cancer cells, meaning that it h=
as the same molecular formula as in normal cells but a different chemical s=
tructure.=20
That means that the researchers were able to develop a small molecule drug =
that can interfere with PCNA in cancer cells but not in healthy cells, stop=
ping the replication and thus the spread of the cancerous cells. The drug k=
illed 100% of solid tumors across 70 cancer types in vitro and in animal mo=
dels.
There=E2=80=99s a few things you need to know here:
It=E2=80=99s still early: Phase 1 trials are getting underway, and even if =
proven safe and effective, we=E2=80=99re likely a few years away from wides=
pread adoption. FWIW, Manifold currently has its legitimacy at 35% [ https:=
//link.sbstck.com/redirect/494e852c-12b7-4173-85d7-39886109608f?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Safe with Low Side Effects: According to the paper, the drug has few if any=
 side effects. It has a therapeutic index (ratio between the dose that can =
help you versus the dose that can harm you) of 6, which is fairly good for =
a cancer drug.
Slows Tumor Growth: The drug slows tumor growth on its own or with a combin=
ation of other therapeutics.=20
For those keeping score at home, in the past 10 days we=E2=80=99ve gotten a=
 (possible) room-temperature superconductor and now a safe and effective ca=
ncer killing drug. We are so back.=20
(2) WTF Happened In 2023? [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/4b41d6b7-46a9-=
4a97-b283-e5668bde7f12?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy McCormick for Not Boring
At the same time, we=E2=80=99re in a period of technological acceleration. =
We talk about it all the time here: AI finally works, the economics of spac=
e pencil out, fusion startups are making progress, renewable energy is boom=
ing, and now we might even get room-temperature superconductors. Optimism s=
hapes reality, and an optimistic foundation is necessary to leverage instea=
d of impede the benefits of these technologies.=C2=A0
We are so fricken back. And we even thought this before we found out about =
this new cancer killing drug. Now we can add that to the list.
About 14 months ago, Packy laid out his (and Not Boring=E2=80=99s) worldvie=
w in a widely-shared essay titled Optimism [ https://link.sbstck.com/redire=
ct/88883802-ef10-4409-8015-ed4f03fe093a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. At the time, things seemed bleak; raging=
 inflation, a looming recession, the war in Ukraine, and a washing away of =
ZIRP-fueled tech momentum. To me, and many folks out there, it felt like a =
weird time to be overly optimistic.
Flash forward 14 months and we=E2=80=99ve gotten:
AI that finally works
A booming renewable energy industry
Q>1 fusion reaction
Quantum computing milestones
A strong economy in the U.S. [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/61acbded-bc=
18-454c-a51c-5e9c942e86a5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Potential  room-temperature superconductor
That=E2=80=99s just a short list of the >250 accomplishments we=E2=80=99ve =
shared in the Weekly Dose of Optimism over the last year. Outside of this l=
ittle newsletter we write, we=E2=80=99re sensing that the winds are shiftin=
g. Pessimism is out and optimism is in.=20
(FWIW, I edit all of Packy=E2=80=99s essays. I=E2=80=99d say 50% I enjoy, 4=
0% I really enjoy, and 10% have me running through a wall. WTF Happened in =
2023? [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/4b41d6b7-46a9-4a97-b283-e5668bde7f=
12?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] fal=
ls in that last category.)
(3) Ensuring U.S. Leadership in the Critical and Emerging Technologies of t=
he 21st Century [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a51d87ee-2f61-4cec-8fe1-=
c72d7c25839d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ]
Josh Wolfe in front of The Select Committee on the Chinese Communist Party
Josh Wolfe, a co-founder and managing partner at Lux Capital, testified in =
front of Congress this week on the importance of American leadership in cri=
tical and emerging technologies. As mentioned above, we=E2=80=99re experien=
cing breakneck progress in a bunch of these fields right now =E2=80=94 ever=
ything from AI, to biotech, to quantum computing. All of this work is impor=
tant and America should strive to be the place where that innovation happen=
s and where the world=E2=80=99s brightest come to do that work.
Wolfe also called to attention the critical importance of American leadersh=
ip in nuclear energy [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/39b4163b-58fa-4051-=
876e-ad8133e740c3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ], an area in which he believes the U.S. has fallen behind China =
in recent years. While the number of nuclear reactors in the U.S. decreases=
, China is building up capacity quickly. And more importantly, they=E2=80=
=99re exporting this technology and know-how to the developing world =E2=80=
=94 regions like Africa and Latin America, that desperately need affordable=
 sources of energy to keep up development. In doing so, China is building u=
p these regions=E2=80=99 dependency on them for decades to come.
Sometimes, it takes competition to snap out of complacency. America=E2=80=
=99s heating rivalry with the CCP may be the push we need to make smarter d=
ecisions on immigration, nuclear energy, and technological leadership where=
 it counts.=20
(4) This Bay Area startup will help steer billions of dollars toward clean =
energy investments [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/f5b4da49-5a71-4ef4-9d=
88-274cec92e95b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]
Patrick Sisson for Fast Company
WattCarbon buyers would invest money in a fractional share of a project por=
tfolio=E2=80=94electrifying lower-income buildings in a specific neighborho=
od that otherwise wouldn=E2=80=99t get the investment, installing solar pan=
els in a region with coal-powered utilities, or subsidizing the deployment =
of fossil-fuel-free appliances, for example. Those funds would then be rele=
ased to the supplier to help pay for the project, including staff and equip=
ment.
Not Boring Capital portfolio company, WattCarbon [ https://link.sbstck.com/=
redirect/826f4476-282c-4c92-8c68-906d04bd6cd4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], got some very nice ink in Fast Com=
pany this week for its decarbonization marketplace. Through WattCarbon, buy=
ers invest in projects that speed up electrification, have a measurable imp=
act, and show clear progress toward cutting emissions. It=E2=80=99s in some=
 ways similar a carbon-offset marketplace, but for the built-world.=20
Carbon offset schemes have come under scrutiny in the last couple of years,=
 where companies can invest in projects like tree-planting, a long-term, wo=
rk-intensive, and hard-to-measure solution. In contrast, the types of proje=
cts WattCarbon funds help directly avoid future emissions. The company is s=
tarting with decarbonizing buildings. According to the Brookings Institute,=
 decarbonizing buildings will eliminate 40% of annual GHG emissions, enough=
 to meet the goals of the Paris Climate Accords.
Decarbonizing the built world is a tall task, but just the type of task we =
like funding at Not Boring Capital and writing about in the Weekly Dose.
(5) Vial: Reimagining Clinical Trials [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/19=
a13c1b-c1fa-4ec5-bb5b-6c3c5ad5dab5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By Elliot Hershberg in Century of Biology
If we don=E2=80=99t think we can genuinely make a dent in treating nearly a=
ll diseases by the end of this century, we aren=E2=80=99t taking ourselves =
seriously. There are still enormous challenges to tackle, like inventing ne=
w drug delivery approaches [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a8b445f4-d3f8=
-4b1b-adf7-38cc89459e25?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and solving the manufacturing bottleneck for medicines, b=
ut this is where great scientists and engineers shine. A broader problem lo=
oms:
Do we have the infrastructure to test all of the new medicines we=E2=80=99r=
e inventing?
Packy here. I=E2=80=99m biased Elliot [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/7c=
d642c8-6c43-485b-af3e-4a05383f3f1a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is part of the Not Boring family, but his piec=
e this week on the clinical trial startup Vial [ https://link.sbstck.com/re=
direct/5cb0c953-690a-44ee-9fb6-d260e43907ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] was one of the best startup deep dive=
s I=E2=80=99ve read in a long time. It had everything: nuanced understandin=
g of incentives, a bold vision to tackle a hard problem, smart strategy, an=
d Kanye lyrics. It also had one of my favorite things to see: startup veter=
ans applying their experience to Good Quests [ https://link.sbstck.com/redi=
rect/4362331d-d036-46d4-9981-1508c2d65a6a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Vial co-founders Simon Burns and Andrew Brackin came from outside of the he=
althcare industry, identified clinical trials as a major bottleneck with th=
e right incentive structure to be fixable, and doggedly mapped out the whol=
e process (seen above). Then, they digitized and automated the whole thing,=
 turning it into their first product: TrialOS, with the goal of driving a 1=
0x improvement in both the cost and speed of clinical trials. It=E2=80=99s =
already working to the tune of tens of millions of dollars in revenue.=20
Now, they=E2=80=99re launching their second act: Battery Bio [ https://link=
=2Esbstck.com/redirect/ea0954b6-561c-4=
292-b7e9-ab15cd0f3070?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CAI-POWERED HY=
PER SCALABLE BIOTECH.=E2=80=9D With Battery, they=E2=80=99re vertically int=
egrating the drug development process and leveraging their advantage in tri=
als to =E2=80=9Ctest dozens, or even hundreds, of new medicines in parallel=
=2E=E2=80=9D With Battery, Vial aims to la=
unch over 1,000 programs on the pla=
tform, an order of magnitude more than even Merck. It=E2=80=99s early, but =
there are already 21 programs moving towards trial launch.=20
Vial is a textbook Hard Startup: instead of complaining about the cost and =
speed of clinical trials, they=E2=80=99re solving the problem themselves, a=
nd then vertically integrating to take advantage of a world of cheap, fast =
clinical trials and software-led drug development. It=E2=80=99s hard not to=
 be optimistic in the face of that scale of ambition.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

